<div class="two_column_left" style = "font-size: 0.9em">
    <strong>How are Keywords used?</strong>
    <br /><br />
    We try to make it as easy as possible for users to find exactly the training they're looking for.  They can 
    search by group or category and by location (within a region, a country, or a defined distance).
    <br /><br />
    We're deliberately keeping the T4T categories general.  For example, 'HR', 'Sales', 'Accountancy' are 
    three categories in the 'Jobs' group.  But each of these categories could include a vast array of 
    different training options.  For example, HR training might focus on manpower planning, attendance, 
    payroll, recruitment, appraisal, training itself - or all of these.  And while some programs will be 
    aimed at beginners, others will be for experienced HR staff, or perhaps even for non-HR managers who need
    a better understanding of what HR can offer.  
    <br /><br />
    If we allowed for all these distinctions at the category level, users would need to search through
    lists thousands of items long to find what they need.  That's not what we want.
    <br /><br />
    Instead we use Keywords.  Vendors can attach up to 15 actual words as keywords to each of their 
    training resources.  And when users search or set up their permanent preferences, they'll make location, 
    group and category selections (optionally also, a format preference - e.g <i>'I want online 
    training'</i>); then they enter up to 10 keywords as well.
    <br /><br />
    T4T will then determine the best matches, starting with location, group and category, but then 
    fine-tuning with the keywords.  The resources with the most matching keywords will be given the 
    highest priority.
    <br /><br />
    <i>(User review scores are also important.  Where the number of keyword matches are the same, the 
    resource with the highest review scores will be listed first.)</i>
    <br /><br />
    When users are actively searching for training, T4T starts with the user's preferences, and then tracks 
    down matching vendor resources.
    <br /><br />
    But when a vendor issues a discounted T4T ticket, it works the other way round.  T4T looks for users whose
    location, group and category preferences fit, and then does a keyword match.  While users have the website
    open <i>(or, if they prefer, via an email notification)</i>, they'll see a list of the current tickets 
    that match all their preferences and at least one of their keywords.  Again, the list will be 
    prioritized by the number of keyword matches (and then by user review scores).
    <br /><br />
    The result, we hope, will be a search and selection methodology that's easy to use, but always provides
    relevant results.  Users should see only the training that's likely to interest them, while vendor 
    promotions will be targeted precisely at the people who are most likely to buy.  
