<div class="two_column_right" style = "font-size: 0.9em">
    <strong>Building your Keyword list</strong>
    <br /><br />
    Keywords can be a single word or a cluster of words, with each separated from the next by a comma.  Let's
    take a look at an example of a well-written keyword set. 
    <br /><br />
    <div class="description"><i>guitar, acoustic, folk, chords, finger picking, chord diagrams, audio examples, 
      beginner, learn songs</i>
    </div>
    <br />
    With these 9 keywords (using 13 words - the maximum allowed is 15 actual words), anyone should have a
    pretty clear idea what the training is about.  If I want to be a guitar hero playing electric rock, this
    course probably isn't for me.  And if I'm already an experienced guitarist it's probably too easy.  But
    if I'm starting out and want to learn to play folk-style, and I've had that old acoustic guitar for 
    years, then this could be a good way to get started.
    <br /><br />
    The keywords don't include anything about 'learning to play'.  Why not?  Because this training resource
    is in the 'Fun' group, categorized as 'Playing a musical instrument'.  Users select a category, then enter
    their keyword preferences - so you don't need to repeat the category.
    <br /><br />
    Similarly, keywords don't need to include the training format, because that will be picked up from the 
    main description.  This particular course happens to be an online program - this will be shown in the
    search results.  And if users wish to specify a preference for a particular learning format, they can do
    so, and T4T will limit the results accordingly.
    <br /><br />
    It is important to define the type of learner who'll benefit most from the training - in this case, it's
    a 'beginner'.  Other useful level indicators could be: - <i>managers, experienced, trainee, induction, 
    professional</i>. 
    <br /><br />
    If the training is preparation for a well-known qualification (our guitar course isn't), then include the
    qualification as a keyword.  But always remember that an effective keyword is one that's likely to appear
    in user search lists, so there's not much point in listing a little-known qualification or an internal
    certificate.
    <br /><br />
    The key is to imagine yourself as one of your own potential clients - but someone who's never come 
    across your training before.  What would their keyword preference list look like?  There's help 
    available.  If you click on <i>Popular keywords</i>, you'll see a list of the most
    popular keywords for the current category.
    <br /><br />
    Finally, check your resource description again.  Does it prompt you to add new keywords?  And are some of
    your keywords in the description too?  If not, they should be, to reinforce your message. 
    
    
</div>


